<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42335650</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-5835</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>167</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>17</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Leukemia research</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Leuk Res</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Long-term remission and survival in older adults with IDH-mutated acute myeloid leukemia treated with IDH inhibitors.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>108268</StartPage><MedlinePgn>108268</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.leukres.2026.108268</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0145-2126(26)00112-8</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Isocitrate dehydrogenase inhibitors (IDHi) for IDH-mutated acute myeloid leukemia (AML) are important treatment options for older adults in whom treatment-related toxicities are a major concern. Long-term data on IDHi are limited.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">We conducted a single-center retrospective study of patients aged &#x2265;&#x202f;65 years with newly diagnosed or relapsed/refractory IDH-mutated AML who received ivosidenib or enasidenib for &#x2265;&#x202f;2 continuous years and either achieved complete remission (CR) or initiated therapy in CR as maintenance.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Nine patients were identified with median treatment duration of 6.88 years (range: 1.94-8.87). Median age at IDHi initiation was 71 years (range: 65-84); 44% were &#x2265;&#x202f;75 years. Six patients (67%) had IDH1 mutations and 3 (33%) had IDH2 mutations. Median number of mutated genes per patient was 4 (range: 1-6). There were no mutations in the receptor tyrosine kinase pathway. Four patients began IDHi at diagnosis, 3 upon relapse, and 2 as maintenance following first CR. No differentiation syndrome occurred. Seven patients (78%) remain on IDHi and in CR; both who relapsed had antecedent myeloid neoplasms. At median follow-up of 6.88 years (range: 2.62-8.87), median event-free survival (EFS) and overall survival (OS) were not reached. Five-year EFS and OS were 78% (95% CI: 55-100) and 88% (95% CI: 67-100), respectively.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">This selected real-world cohort demonstrates durable responses exceeding published benchmarks and has one of the longest follow-up periods reported for IDHi in AML. A subset of older adults with IDH-mutated AML can achieve highly durable remissions on IDHi without significant toxicity.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kapoor</LastName><ForeName>Nilesh</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Internal Medicine, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA. Electronic address: nilesh.kapoor@utsouthwestern.edu.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hoff</LastName><ForeName>Fieke W</ForeName><Initials>FW</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Hematology Branch, National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, MD, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jackson</LastName><ForeName>Clayton</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gatell</LastName><ForeName>Vivian Irizarry</ForeName><Initials>VI</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Arslan</LastName><ForeName>Shukaib</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Velarde</LastName><ForeName>Alejandro Marinos</ForeName><Initials>AM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Collins</LastName><ForeName>Robert H</ForeName><Initials>RH</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chung</LastName><ForeName>Stephen S</ForeName><Initials>SS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Madanat</LastName><ForeName>Yazan F</ForeName><Initials>YF</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Harold C. Simmons Comprehensive Cancer Center, UT Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>17</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>England</Country><MedlineTA>Leuk Res</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>7706787</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>0145-2126</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Acute myeloid leukemia</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Geriatric oncology</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Isocitrate dehydrogenase inhibitors</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Targeted therapy</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>Declaration of Competing Interest All authors declare no competing interests relevant to this work. No funding was received for this study.</CoiStatement></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2026</Year><Month>4</Month><Day>14</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="revised"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>30</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>14</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>24</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>46</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>24</Day><Hour>0</Hour><Minute>46</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>6</Month><Day>23</Day><Hour>18</Hour><Minute>5</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">42335650</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1016/j.leukres.2026.108268</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">S0145-2126(26)00112-8</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42182206</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>25</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>25</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2692-8205</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>17</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>bioRxiv : the preprint server for biology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>bioRxiv</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Subclonal IDH1/2 Mutations as a Targetable Vulnerability in Vascular Tumors.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">2026.05.14.725132</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.64898/2026.05.14.725132</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="UNLABELLED">Despite extensive sequencing, the genetic etiology of sporadic angiosarcoma remains poorly defined (1-3). Maffucci syndrome, characterized by vascular tumors and elevated cancer risk, is driven by mosaic gain-of-function mutations in IDH1/2 (4,5), though these have not been reported in sporadic angiosarcoma. We identify recurrent, low-variant allele frequency hotspot mutations in <i>IDH1/2</i> in over half of sporadic angiosarcomas. Mutations were validated by Sanger sequencing and immunohistochemistry. Mutant IDH1 endothelial cells promote tumorigenesis through non-cell-autonomous mechanisms, secreting 2-hydroxyglutarate (2-HG) to increase growth factor and endothelial-to-mesenchymal transition gene expression, activate pAkt/pERK signaling, induce DNA methylation changes, and promote anchorage-independent growth, which are reversed by the mutant IDH1 inhibitor ivosidenib. Patients with mosaic IDH1 mutations show reduced serum 2-HG and marked tumor regression following ivosidenib treatment. The clinical efficacy of ivosidenib in vascular tumors with subclonal IDH1 mutations suggests that low VAF <i>IDH1/2</i> mutations may be a targetable vulnerability in sporadic angiosarcoma. (6,7).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="STATEMENT OF SIGNIFICANCE" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">We identify recurrent, low-VAF IDH1/2 mutations in angiosarcoma and provide evidence that these subclonal mutations promote tumorigenesis through non-cell-autonomous mechanisms. Vascular tumors driven by subclonal IDH1 mutations responded dramatically to ivosidenib, thus revealing a novel treatment for a subset of vascular tumors.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Yu</LastName><ForeName>Dong-Min</ForeName><Initials>DM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lee</LastName><ForeName>Eunice</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Starrett</LastName><ForeName>Gabriel J</ForeName><Initials>GJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-5871-5306</Identifier></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhai</LastName><ForeName>Zili</ForeName><Initials>Z</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dowell</LastName><ForeName>Eleanor</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Walsh</LastName><ForeName>Kaitlyn</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Day</LastName><ForeName>Andrew</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Palsgrove</LastName><ForeName>Doreen</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bishop</LastName><ForeName>Justin</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Marchione</LastName><ForeName>Dylan M</ForeName><Initials>DM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Asgari</LastName><ForeName>Maryam</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chung</LastName><ForeName>Stephen</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>High</LastName><ForeName>Whitney</ForeName><Initials>W</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Teng</LastName><ForeName>Joyce Mc</ForeName><Initials>JM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wisell</LastName><ForeName>Josh</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wilky</LastName><ForeName>Breelyn A</ForeName><Initials>BA</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Glass</LastName><ForeName>Donald A</ForeName><Initials>DA</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hosler</LastName><ForeName>Gregory A</ForeName><Initials>GA</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Richard C</ForeName><Initials>RC</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-4543-8295</Identifier></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D000076942">Preprint</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>17</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>bioRxiv</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101680187</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>2692-8205</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>25</Day><Hour>12</Hour><Minute>36</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>25</Day><Hour>12</Hour><Minute>35</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>25</Day><Hour>8</Hour><Minute>7</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pmc-release"><Year>2026</Year><Month>5</Month><Day>21</Day></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>epublish</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">42182206</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC13192967</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.64898/2026.05.14.725132</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">2026.05.14.725132</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">42167507</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>21</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2589-5559</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>20</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>JHEP reports : innovation in hepatology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>JHEP Rep</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>IDH1 R132 mutations or HER2-positivity and benefit from platinum-based therapy for biliary tract cancers.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>101899</StartPage><MedlinePgn>101899</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.jhepr.2026.101899</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S2589-5559(26)00170-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND &amp; AIMS" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">Targeted therapies for biliary tract cancers (BTC) are approved in second line. We investigated response to first-line platinum-based palliative systemic anti-cancer treatment in patients with the most common druggable alterations to determine the optimal positioning of targeted therapies in the treatment algorithm.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Patients treated at the Beatson West of Scotland centralized BTC clinic who underwent genomic profiling were retrospectively selected; those with the most common actionable alterations who received platinum-based treatment were included in clinical analyses. Observations were supported by tracking IDH1 mutations with digital droplet PCR on longitudinal cell free DNA samples.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">39.7% of patients had druggable alterations; HER2 overexpression/amplification and IDH1 R132 mutations were the most common ones. Compared to patients with HER2-positive tumors (N=11), patients with IDH1 R132 mutations (N=6) had longer median time to best response (5.99 vs 2.5 months; HR 0.28; 95%CI, 0.09-0.91; p=0.0033), and median time to progression (TTP) (17.2 vs 5.6 months; HR 0.266; 95%CI, 0.0955-0.741; p=0.0075). Compared to a cohort of patients without either alterations, those with IDH1-mutated BTC had longer median overall survival (OS) (HR 0.30; 95%CI, 0.14-0.67; p=0.0229); those with HER2-positive BTC showed a worse median TTP (HR 1.97; 95%CI, 0.85-4.58; p=0.0408) and a trend towards worse median OS (HR 1.38; 95%CI, 0.61-3.13; p=0.3884). IDH1 VAF decreased during first line, regardless of response; prolonged benefit from ivosidenib in second line was observed when VAF was &lt;1 at start of targeted treatment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">These preliminary data might indicate that targeted therapies should be introduced in first line with different strategies depending on molecular alterations, with access to platinum-based palliative systemic anti-cancer treatment being important for patients with IDH1-mutated BTC.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="IMPACT AND IMPLICATIONS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">We conducted an analysis to determine whether patients with biliary tract cancer harboring the most common actionable alterations (i.e. IDH1 R132 mutations and HER2 overexpression or amplification) had different patterns of response to first-line platinum-based chemo(immuno)therapy. The goal was to determine whether the introduction of targeted therapies in first line should have a tailored approach based on the alteration detected. In our cohort, patients with IDH1 R132 mutations had durable benefit from platinum-based chemotherapy, while those with HER2-positive tumors had a short-lived benefit from it. While our results are speculative in nature due to the small sample size, they may inform future approaches to the implementation of targeted agents in an earlier setting, with appropriate design of large clinical trials.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026. Published by Elsevier B.V.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tesini</LastName><ForeName>Giulia</ForeName><Initials>G</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Cancer Sciences, University of Glasgow, Glasgow G61 1BD, UK; Department of Biomedical Sciences, Humanitas University, Via Rita Levi Montalcini, 4, 20072 Pieve Emanuele, Milan, Italy.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Greaves</LastName><ForeName>Jack</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Cancer Sciences, University of Glasgow, Glasgow G61 1